---
import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import Hero from '../components/Hero.astro';
import FeatureBlock from '../components/FeatureBlock.astro';
import CalloutBand from '../components/CalloutBand.astro';
---

<BaseLayout title="Our Home — Paws on Longmeadow">
  <Hero
    title="Our Home"
    subtitle="Most mornings start the same way. Marian is up early, coffee in hand, setting the space before the first dog arrives. The quiet before the storm, and she loves it."
  />

  <FeatureBlock heading="Ollie's Deck">
    <p>
      Every dog lands here first. Ollie's Deck is a large outdoor space between the house, the yard,
      and the street, where dogs arrive, decompress, and move between the parts of their day. It has
      Kuranda elevated beds, a water station, and plenty of shade. Three access points keep arrivals,
      departures, and yard time organized and controlled.
    </p>
  </FeatureBlock>

  <FeatureBlock heading="The yard">
    <p>
      The backyard is fully fenced, about 12,000 square feet, with a mix of grass, gravel, and
      natural mulch to explore. Mature trees give shade, and there is always somewhere cool to
      settle. Fencing is six feet tall across most of the perimeter with three secure gates. We treat
      the yard with dog-safe products, keep a regular mosquito and tick schedule, and clean it daily.
    </p>
  </FeatureBlock>

  <FeatureBlock heading="The inside">
    <p>
      During the day dogs have the run of the main level, the living room and kitchen, the places a
      family actually lives. A baby gate keeps things to the first floor. Dogs sleep wherever they
      are most comfortable, from elevated beds to a very popular couch. Boarding dogs are fed
      separately, inside a crate or behind an x-pen, a simple practice that keeps mealtimes calm and
      safe.
    </p>
  </FeatureBlock>

  <FeatureBlock heading="How arrivals work" ctaLabel="See hours and details" ctaHref="/faq">
    <p>
      Drop-off and pickup are curbside. Text us when you are on your way and again when you arrive,
      and we will meet you at the curb. For boarding, bring your dog's food, a blanket, and a familiar
      item or two. We introduce new arrivals to the group slowly and pay attention to how every dog
      enters a space.
    </p>
  </FeatureBlock>

  <CalloutBand
    heading="See it for yourself"
    text="Your Meet & Greet happens right here on Ollie's Deck, so you see exactly where your dog will be."
    ctaLabel="Request a Meet & Greet"
    ctaHref="/request-a-meet-and-greet"
  />
</BaseLayout>
